recommandationVideos.Title: I made a research trip to the Chinese internet
recommandationVideos.Description:
This China Trilogy is intended to explain China: What is it? Where does it come from? Where is it going? What does it want? On the one hand, this is motivated by my own interest in the subject, but I also think that for Finns in general, China is a bit of a mysterious country, even though it is increasingly in the news. So there might be a demand for something like this.

In this first episode, I'm adventuring on the Chinese internet and trying to find out how Chinese people at grassroots level see China. In Chinese social media, memes, politics and censorship are intertwined into a multi-leveled whole.

recommandationVideos.Description:
China‚Äôs Uighur minority live a dystopian nightmare of constant surveillance and brutal policing. VICE News‚Äô Isobel Yeung posed as a tourist to gain unprecedented access to China‚Äôs western Xinjiang region, which has been nearly unreachable by journalists.

She and our crew experienced China‚Äôs Orwellian surveillance and harassment first-hand during their time in Xinjiang, and captured chilling hidden-camera footage of eight Uighur men detained by police in the middle of the night. We spoke with members of the Uighur community about their experience in these camps, and about China‚Äôs attempts to silence their history and lifestyle under the cover of darkness.

recommandationVideos.Title: China‚Äôs Vanishing Muslims: Undercover In The Most Dystopian Place In The World
Keywords: they come for us at night hbo
recommandationVideos.Description:
China‚Äôs Uighur minority live a dystopian nightmare of constant surveillance and brutal policing. At least one million of them are believed to be living in what the U.N. described as a ‚Äúmassive internment camp that is shrouded in secrecy,‚Äù while many Uighur children are taken to state-run orphanages where they're indoctrinated into Chinese customs.

The Uighurs' plight has largely been kept hidden from the world, thanks to China‚Äôs aggressive attempts to suppress the story at all costs.

VICE News‚Äô Isobel Yeung posed as a tourist to gain unprecedented access to China‚Äôs western Xinjiang region, which has been nearly unreachable by journalists.

She and our crew experienced China‚Äôs Orwellian surveillance and harassment first-hand during their time in Xinjiang, and captured chilling hidden-camera footage of eight Uighur men detained by police in the middle of the night. We spoke with members of the Uighur community about their experience in these camps, and about China‚Äôs attempts to silence their history and lifestyle under the cover of darkness.

recommandationVideos.Title: The Greco-Chinese War Over the Heavenly Horses
recommandationVideos.Description:
In our previous animated historical documentary we have talked about the Ancient Greek state in Bactria (http://bit.ly/2RJpa5u), but this Hellenistic state had to fight a number of wars after the conquests of Alexander. The Greeks of the region (Dayuan) were discovered by China during the expedition of the traveler Zhang Qian and had to fight against the Han dynasty during the War of the Heavenly horses between 104 and 101 BC. this war changed the fate of the region, and contributed to the creation of the Silk Road.

Check out this playlist to learn more about Ancient warfare: https://goo.gl/UpuKku

recommandationVideos.Title: What Singaporeans Think Of China | Street Interview
recommandationVideos.Description:
Did you know that according to a recent survey, Singapore is one of the only countries in the Indo-Pacific that has more favorable views of China compared to the US? We wanted to find out directly from the locals how accurate they think this survey is. So our Asian Boss reporter hit the streets of Singapore to find out what the locals really think of China. The opinions expressed in this video are those of individual interviewees alone and do not reflect the views of ASIAN BOSS or the general Singaporean population.

0:00 - Intro 
1:08 - What are your personal views of China? 
3:05 - Singaporean media coverage of China 
4:01 - Do you think Singaporeans prefer China over the US? 
6:37 - Singaporeans on Taiwanese independence 
8:15 - Chinese influences in Singapore 
9:20 - Factors that influence people's opinions on China 
11:40 - Should Singapore work more closely with the US or China? 
13:42 - How can Singapore maintain a good relationship with both China and the US?

resultVideos.Title: I made a research trip to the Chinese internet
resultVideos.Description:
This China Trilogy is intended to explain China: What is it? Where does it come from? Where is it going? What does it want? On the one hand, this is motivated by my own interest in the subject, but I also think that for Finns in general, China is a bit of a mysterious country, even though it is increasingly in the news. So there might be a demand for something like this.

In this first episode, I'm adventuring on the Chinese internet and trying to find out how Chinese people at grassroots level see China. In Chinese social media, memes, politics and censorship are intertwined into a multi-leveled whole.

recommandationVideos.Description:
Seven year van-iversary! Time goes so quickly when you have a good time. In this podcast episode we talk with our first language. There is subtitles in english are available. Thanks for watching our channel.

Timestamps in this episode:
0:36 Intro

45:30 How much does it costs to live in a van?

FAQ
About Vantastic: We are a happy couple who got rid of everything to travel the world. We make vlogs sharing our daily lives in a camper van, our ups and downs, and our adventures around Europe. 

What camera equipment do you use?
We use GoPro10, R√∏de VideoMicro with a dead kitten, Ulanzi tripod mt-16, Ulanzi cage G9, Ulanzi vl49 light, DJ Mavic Pro drone and Adobe Premiere Pro to edit the vlogs. Our electrical power set-up in our camper van allows charging our camera and laptops to film and edit.

What is your van?
Our camper van is Fiat Ducato 2015, Adria Twin conversion panel van. We have done only minor upgrades and mods to our camper van, we pretty much love it as it is. 

How do you afford your nomadic lifestyle?
We live on a true shoestring budget. We travel economically, we cook all our meals, we dont visit tourist traps, we enjoy being in the nature and hiking in the nature. We worked traditional office jobs for years and now we live on our savings and investments. We dont believe you need tons of money to to pursue your passion. However, we have learned that you do need to sacrifice comfort, consistency and safety, but that it is possible, very worth it, and the only lifestyle that makes us truly happy!

What happens after van life?
Call us naive, but our goal is to travel forever.

recommandationVideos.Title: Terracotta Army, Xian, China  [Amazing Places 4K]
recommandationVideos.Description:
The Terracotta Army was created during the reign of the first emperor of China's Qin dynasty (221-207 B.C.), to protect the emperor's tomb. 700,000 people probably worked on the site, near the city of Xian, for almost three decades. More than 8000 figures have been excavated so far. The tomb has been designated a UNESCO World Heritage site.

Recorded October 2015 in 4K (Ultra HD) with Sony AX100.

recommandationVideos.Description:
China Built The World's Largest Ice City (Melts In 1 Month)
Harbin Ice Festival in China

I came to Harbin, a city of over 5 million people in northeast China. Harbin is very famous for its yearly Harbin Ice Festival. Millions of (mostly Chinese) tourists come to visit Harbin every winter to see the impressive ice city they built here. The whole area is about 800.000sqm large and it's super viral all over Chinese social media. The big problem though: It is also freezing cold in Harbin. The temperatures can get down to -30 ¬∞C/-22 ¬∞F. It's the coldest place I have ever been to! Will I be able to handle the cold? And how impressive is the Harbin Ice Festival really? Let's find out!

It is actually a network of fortifications rather than a single structure, and is the product of countless labors over a period of some two thousand years. recommandationVideos.Title: Terracotta Army, Xian, China  [Amazing Places 4K]
recommandationVideos.Description:
The Terracotta Army was created during the reign of the first emperor of China's Qin dynasty (221-207 B.C.), to protect the emperor's tomb. 700,000 people probably worked on the site, near the city of Xian, for almost three decades. More than 8000 figures have been excavated so far. The tomb has been designated a UNESCO World Heritage site.
